[5] Healthy young male fatality
Date: Fri 24 Jan 2020
Source: MSN News/The Washington Post [abridged, edited]
https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/healthy-young-man-dies-of-coronavirus-in-china-new-cases-in-japan-and-south-korea/ar-BBZh7lo


A young, healthy man from Wuhan and a person living 1500 miles from the epicenter of the coronavirus are among the latest victims of the outbreak, which has incited fear and anger across China as the important Spring Festival gets underway. Reports of 8 new deaths from the pneumonia-like virus, taking the total to 26, came as authorities enforced a lockdown across large parts of the province of Hubei, population 59 million. But they also came as the medical system clearly struggled to cope with the outbreak, with reports of crowded hospitals, stressed doctors and dwindling supplies.

Amid increasing talk that the real number of deaths and infections could be much higher than the official figures, the State Council, the Chinese equivalent of the cabinet, vowed to "seriously handle" underreporting of cases.

Some details about the latest deaths in China have raised concerns about the virus's spread. Until now, the vast majority of the victims had been older than 60, and almost all of them had existing health conditions. All had been in Hubei province and especially in its capital, Wuhan.

But the latest announcement said that a 36-year-old man from Wuhan died on Thursday [23 Jan 2020]. He had no chronic diseases or other existing health conditions and had been treated with anti-virus medication and antibiotics since being admitted to a hospital on [9 Jan 2020].

Another death occurred in Suihua in Heilongjiang province, near the border with Russia and some 1500 miles from Wuhan.

[Byline: Anna Fifield]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[It is not surprising to find an "outlier" in terms of age-group, or in a case imported to another province. I've often wondered when these reports arrive, if the individual did not have an as yet undiagnosed underlying illness leading to an immunosuppression. Unfortunately I suspect we will see an increasing toll of fatalities as the number of cases climbs. - Mod.MPP]

