- Malaysia ex China
Date: Sat 25 Jan 2020
Source: Straits Times [abridged, edited]
https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysia-confirms-first-cases-of-wuhan-coronavirus-infection


Three people have been confirmed to have the Wuhan coronavirus in Malaysia, Malaysian Health Minister Dzulkefly Ahmad said on Saturday ([25 Jan 2020]), marking the 1st cases there of the potentially deadly disease. The 3 Chinese citizens, who entered Malaysia via Johor Baru, are the wife and grandchildren of a 66-year-old man from Wuhan who is currently being treated in Singapore for the same virus. The 3 patients have since been transferred to Sungai Buloh Hospital in Selangor, said Datuk Seri Dzulkefly.

The patients were said to have boarded a plane from Guangzhou to Singapore on [20 Jan 2020]. The 66-year-old man and his son tested positive for the virus and were admitted to hospital in Singapore on [22 Jan 2020].

There were a total of 9 people in the group who were travelling together with the 1st male patient: his wife, son, daughter-in-law, 2 grandchildren and another family of 4 comprising husband and wife and 2 children.

They were quarantined upon arrival in Johor while awaiting test results for the virus. Initial tests had found that they were not experiencing fever or any other symptoms.

